<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Mississippi's solar irradiance levels average 4.9 kWh/m¬≤/day, placing it in the upper tier of U.S. states for solar potential. The state receives consistent sunlight throughout the year, with peak production months from April through September averaging 5.2-5.8 daily sun hours. Even during winter months, Mississippi maintains respectable solar production with 3.5-4.2 daily sun hours, ensuring year-round energy generation.</p>

<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in Mississippi can produce approximately 8,500-9,500 kWh annually, depending on roof orientation, shading, and system efficiency. South-facing installations with minimal shading achieve optimal performance, while east and west-facing systems still produce 85-90% of south-facing capacity. The state's relatively low latitude (30-35¬∞N) allows for excellent solar panel performance with optimal tilt angles between 28-32 degrees.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations are moderate compared to northern states, with summer production exceeding winter by approximately 40-50%. This production pattern aligns well with Mississippi's energy consumption patterns, where air conditioning drives peak summer electricity usage. Cloud cover and weather patterns typical of the Gulf Coast region result in approximately 180-200 clear sunny days annually, with partial sun conditions adding significant production throughout the year.</p>

