<h2>HVAC Systems in Mississippi</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Mississippi's humid subtropical climate creates specific HVAC requirements that differ significantly from other regions. The state experiences long, hot summers with high humidity levels often exceeding 70%, requiring robust cooling systems that can handle both temperature and moisture control. Cooling degree days average 2,400-2,800 annually, while heating degree days range from only 1,800-2,400, indicating that cooling represents the primary energy load for most Mississippi homes.</p>

<p>For optimal performance in Mississippi's climate, HVAC systems should feature SEER ratings of at least 15-16, with high-efficiency units rated 18-20 SEER providing the best long-term value. Heat pumps are particularly well-suited for Mississippi's mild winters, as they can efficiently provide heating when outdoor temperatures remain above 25¬∞F, which covers the vast majority of winter conditions. Dual-fuel systems combining heat pumps with gas furnace backup offer excellent efficiency and reliability for the occasional extreme cold snaps.</p>

<p>Humidity control is critical in Mississippi HVAC design. Systems should include proper dehumidification capabilities, often requiring variable-speed air handlers and appropriately sized equipment to maintain indoor humidity levels between 40-50%. Oversized systems that short-cycle fail to adequately remove humidity, leading to comfort issues and potential mold problems. Proper ductwork design and sealing are essential, as leaky ducts in Mississippi's humid climate can introduce moisture and significantly reduce system efficiency.</p>

